-      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 6 puts Transparency Diligence in writing as a Week 6 discipline | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 6 \"Worked Example: An Output Trace\" closing line \"That division of labor is Diligence — knowing what's yours to own in every AI-assisted output.\"; ai_fluency_framework.html 4Ds section, Diligence card with \"Transparency Diligence\" sub-competency \"Transparency and accountability when distributing end products\")\nClaim: Worked example shows a success coach editing a Claude-drafted email to a student with at-risk renewal | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html \"Worked Example: An Output Trace\" task description: \"A success coach needs to email a student whose scholarship renewal is at risk because they're under-enrolled this semester.\")\nClaim: Claude produced correct policy info, clear deadline, professional tone | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html \"What Claude Produced\" panel verbatim: \"Correct policy information, clear deadline, professional tone.\")\nClaim: Coach rewrote opening as personal check-in, softened deadline, added two specific actions, included direct phone number | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html \"What Was Actually Sent\" panel verbatim language)\nClaim: Claude Enterprise audit log captures platform-level events but does not reveal conversation contents | Source: GROUNDED (ai_governance_framework.html Section 4 Security & Compliance Configuration, Audit Logging row: \"Enabled, reviewed monthly. Provides visibility into platform usage. Supports compliance documentation. Does not reveal information about specific conversations.\")\nClaim: Week 6 challenge asks for an output trace of one external output, capturing what Claude produced, what was changed, and why | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 6 Challenge box verbatim: \"Find one output you sent externally this week. Trace it like the example above: what did Claude produce, what did you change, and why? Bring the trace to Friday.\")\nClaim: Mapping \"why\" categories to specific 4D competencies (tone → Discernment, next-steps generic → Description, identifier removal → data classification framework) | Source: Editorial (analytical mapping of representative \"why\" notes to the 4Ds defined in ai_fluency_framework.html and the four-tier framework in ai_governance_framework.html Data Classification section)\nClaim: Week 6 Governance Pulse is the four-tier data classification teach-back | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Governance Pulse callout for Week 6-7: \"Teach-back: explain the 4-tier data classification to a colleague who is not in the pilot. If you can't explain it clearly, revisit the framework.\")",
+      "resource": "https://dccapinnovation.org/pilot_hub.html#week-5",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 5 of the pilot (\"Under the Hood\") names model selection as a governance decision in its Governance Pulse | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 block, Governance Pulse callout heading verbatim: \"Governance Pulse — Model Selection IS a Governance Decision\")\nClaim: Defaulting everything to Opus burns nonprofit-tier compute; defaulting to Haiku ships AI-flavored slop; Sonnet is the responsible default | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 Governance Pulse body verbatim: \"Defaulting everything to Opus burns nonprofit-tier compute and slows the team. Defaulting to Haiku ships AI-flavored slop. Sonnet is the responsible default; Opus is reserved for the highest-stakes drafting; Haiku is for lookups and classifications.\")\nClaim: Opus 4.6 is the careful tier for highest-stakes drafting, deep multi-step reasoning, and work where being wrong is costly | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Q5 Opus card: \"Opus 4.6 — careful. Highest-stakes drafting. Deep multi-step reasoning. Board and funder work where being wrong is costly.\")\nClaim: Sonnet 4.6 is the balanced default with strong reasoning, fast enough for everyday work, and handles roughly 80 percent of what DC CAP runs | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Q5 Sonnet card verbatim: \"Sonnet 4.6 — balanced. The DC CAP default. Strong reasoning, fast enough for everyday work. Handles roughly 80% of what you do.\")\nClaim: Haiku 4.5 is the fast tier for quick lookups, classifications, and light summaries; the wrong tool for anything judgment-heavy | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Q5 Haiku card verbatim: \"Haiku 4.5 — fast. Quick lookups. Classifications. Light summaries. The wrong tool for anything judgment-heavy.\")\nClaim: Counselor email goes to Sonnet, Gates LOI to Opus, 10-page PDF summary to Haiku or Sonnet, voice scan on a board memo to Sonnet with extended thinking on | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Q5 \"The move\" line verbatim: \"Counselor email → Sonnet. Gates LOI → Opus. Summarize a 10-page PDF → Haiku or Sonnet. Voice scan on a board memo → Sonnet with thinking on.\")\nClaim: As a team builds Projects and Skills, the builder picks the model for everyone who runs them; \"pick on purpose\" | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 Governance Pulse verbatim: \"Leader scope: as your team builds Projects and Skills, you're picking the model for everyone who runs them. Pick on purpose.\")\nClaim: A Skill pinned to Opus pulls Opus every downstream run; a Skill pinned to Haiku ships sloppy outputs in every downstream chat | Source: Editorial (direct consequence of the GROUNDED leader-scope claim above, applied to pinned model assignments in Skills)\nClaim: Compute is rationed inside the nonprofit tier | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 Governance Pulse phrase \"burns nonprofit-tier compute,\" implying a fixed compute budget at the nonprofit tier)\nClaim: The five-part SHARP-prompt + Description-carried-forward framework underpins the \"deliberate\" model assignment recommended in the Try This | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Q8 SHARP example and \"Save what works\" step, naming Project/Skill as the persistence layer)",
